s well as the effects of globalization, the transmission of social and cultural practices from parents to children is changing. Based on a number of qualitative studies, this book offers insights into the lives of children and youth in Britain, Japan, Spain, Israel/Palestine, and Pakistan. Attention is focused on the child’s perspective within the social-power dynamics involved in adult–child relations, which reveals the dilemmas of policy, planning and parenting in a changing world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aChild developmentvCross-cultural studies. 0aChild psychologyvCross-cultural studies. 0aChildhoodvCross-cultural studies. 0aParentingvCross-cultural studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAbu-Rabia-Queder, Sarab, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarian, Louisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDawson, Elsa L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodman, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaminski, Ignacy-Marek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaminski, Ignacy-Marek, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcNamee, Sally, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Reilly, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRussell, Lucy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeymour, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShah, Nafisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWaldren, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWaldren, Jacqueline, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabular